At the outset of an unprecedented school year, it is only natural for students, staff members and families to look for some indication of what to expect.

In Delano, the first in-person efforts to navigate the COVID-19 virus through various precautions like social distancing, mask-wearing and enhanced cleaning took place in the summer Community Education programming.

“I think the big takeaway is that our community really did pull together through the summer to make these activities happen,” said Youth Development Coordinator Chris Runke. “That’s what it’s going to take to make the school year successful as well..."

See the story at bit.ly/DelanoSummer20

All are welcome to a free presentation by nationally recognized, award-winning children's book author and parenting expert Julia Cook from 7 to 8:30 p.m. on Tuesday, Sept. 1, at the Delano High School Performing Arts Center.

Cook has authored nearly 100 books focused on social development topics. She has been featured in The New Yorker, Parent's Magazine, CNN and other media outlets. Topics in Delano include addressing the COVID-19 situation with children, video game addiction, social skills and more. For details about the event, and to register, see http://bit.ly/CookDelano.

The filing period for the Delano School Board closed yesterday, and five people have stepped forward as candidates in the Nov. 3 general election.

Four individuals are running for three available four-year seats. They are Jim Gierke, Amy Johnson, Regina Lupton and Sue Roeser.

Rachel Depa is unopposed for a two-year seat.

Our thanks to each of these individuals who have indicated a willingness to serve the students, staff and families of Delano Public Schools!

Obscured, perhaps, by the unusual circumstances surrounding the end of the last school year was the departure of one of the district’s most experienced teachers. Second-grade instructor Linda Schmidt retired in June after 33 years with the district, the final three months of which came in an unfamiliar distance learning format.

“She dedicated herself wholeheartedly to her students and the staff at Delano Elementary,” said fellow second-grade teacher Theressa Swan.

“I never really thought about going anywhere else because I knew I wouldn’t find a better staff to work with," said Schmidt.

See the story at bit.ly/SchmidtDES, and please join us in thanking Linda for her outstanding service to our students!

post_text:
Curious what parents around the state are thinking about sending their children back to school this fall, and what they had to say about distance learning? MDE has now released results from its statewide survey, which garnered more than 130,000 responses.

About 64 percent of parents said they feel comfortable sending their students back to school this fall, but nearly a quarter were still unsure and 11.4 percent said they were not. Among those comfortable sending students to school, 94 percent said they preferred to send them back full time. Of those who said they were not comfortable sending their students to school, 83 percent cited public health concerns.

52.6 percent of parents characterized their distance learning experience as negative, while 44.7 percent reported it as positive.

See additional results at https://drive.google.com/file/d/1PjqLacmsK2DCblLv-YvhFexkWJIqIx-R/view?usp=sharing

post_text:
A select group of Delano Intermediate students were honored for outstanding fitness by the physical education department just before the end of the school year.

One dozen students earned the FIT-DIS award, a continuation of what was formerly known as the Presidential Fitness Award. To qualify, a student must score higher than 85 percent of their peers across the nation in every fitness evaluation done in class. Tests include the V-sit (hamstring flexibility), shuttle run (speed and agility), vertical jump (power and muscular strength), pacers (cardio endurance) and sit-ups (muscular endurance).

Congratulations to this year's winners!

Delano Elementary is seeking one full-time or part-time reading tutor, and Delano Intermediate is seeking one full-time math tutor for next school year.

Tutors work with students during school hours throughout the school year. Whether you’re a recent grad, career changer, stay-at-home parent or retiree, you can make a great tutor. No experience? No problem. Tutors receive thorough training, so they are well equipped to help students grow. Tutors commit to serving 35, 25, or 18 hours a week throughout the school year. Opportunities begin in August 2020.

Tutors Receive a paid stipend every two weeks, and earn up to $4,336 for college tuition or student loans. Tutors 55 and older may gift the award to their child, grandchild, stepchild or foster child. Free health insurance and child care assistance is available for those who qualify.

Ready to be the change for struggling students? Learn more at ReadingAndMath.net.

Questions can be sent to join@servetogrow.org, or call 866.859.2825.

Tutors Receive a paid stipend every two weeks, and earn up to $4,336 for college tuition or student loans. Tutors 55 and older may gift the award to their child, grandchild, stepchild or foster child. Free health insurance and child care assistance is available for those who qualify.

Ready to be the change for struggling students? Learn more at ReadingAndMath.net.

Questions can be sent to join@servetogrow.org, or call 866.859.2825.

Thanks to standout performances in “blind” auditions held earlier this year, Mary Leyda, Ryann Wyman and Scarlett Morrissette have earned themselves places in the State Honor Choir.

The fifth-graders at Delano Intermediate School were chosen from audio recordings alone, meaning the judges did not know the name, age or school of the students as they listened to a selection of scales and a short but difficult song in Latin.

“They are rated on accuracy of pitch, rhythms, beautiful tone and musicality,” said DIS choir director Sandy Meyerson. “The auditions were open to fourth-, fifth- and sixth-graders in the state, so our singers were competing with older students with more choral experience, which is a credit to them for their hard work and dedication.” See the story at https://bit.ly/StateHonorDIS.

post_text:
Fourteen Delano students competed in a virtual State History Day competition last weekend after previously advancing through local and regional rounds. Two sixth-grade teams earned honorable mention recognition for their websites.

Alaina Schoepke and Eleanor Hajas presented "Sandra Day O'Connor: A Different Kind Of Justice"; and Carter Van Beusekom, Grayson Poppler and Hayden Rue presented on "Texas Western 1965-66 Championship Season: Paving the Way to Collegiate Integration."

In addition, eighth-graders Larissa Pietila and Peyton Logan won a topical cash prize for their documentary, "Madam CJ Walker: Breaking Barriers as a Business Woman." The prize, sponsored by the Wells Fargo Foundation, goes to outstanding projects focusing on the history of business in the United States between 1852-1930.

Congratulations, students!

post_text:
“Stay at home,” we were told,
So that’s what we did.
But learning continued
For every kid.

“How can we help?”
Asked the food service crew,
Then started in doing
What only they do.

Meals by the hundreds
Were skillfully made
For hungry tummies
In every grade.

With careful precaution
They don mask and glove,
To guard their community,
Serve it with love.

It’s School Lunch Hero Day
Haven’t you heard?
Their cape’s on the front side
And “apron’s” the word
That we use to describe it
But that isn’t right.
We owe them our thanks
In this pandemic fight.

Thank you, Delano food service staff! Your essential work is noticed and very much appreciated!

To guard their community,
Serve it with love.

It’s School Lunch Hero Day
Haven’t you heard?
Their cape’s on the front side
And “apron’s” the word
That we use to describe it
But that isn’t right.
We owe them our thanks
In this pandemic fight.

Thank you, Delano food service staff! Your essential work is noticed and very much appreciated!

“I’ve always wanted to play basketball as far as I can. I love the sport,” Smith said. See the full story at bit.ly/SmithSigning.

Delano's Amy Johnson was one of just 15 school board members from around Minnesota to earn the President’s Award after reaching a milestone in her career of public service this year.

The award goes to those who have attended 300 or more hours of board member training.

“When I decided to run for school board in 2008, it was driven by a strong desire to support the district’s mission statement of academic excellence,” Johnson said. “I always felt that it was my responsibility as a board member to educate myself on the varying issues impacting our students, staff and community in order to be an effective board member."

See the full story at bit.ly/JohnsonAward20.

Since distance learning began on March 30, our food service staff has served more than 300 free meals per day, on average. "This isn't only about providing food for those that need food, but it is about keeping some sense of normalcy for our kids," said Food Service Director Kris Larson. "It is about helping families out during this time in our lives where everything is turned upside down.

"We have had such a positive response from families, and love the special notes we have gotten from kids."

Here are a few of the notes that have kept us smiling (with names removed for privacy). Thank you!

In a show of support for our school community, particularly the senior class of 2020 - and as a symbol of hope that things will eventually return to normal - Delano Public Schools will turn on the lights of Tiger Stadium for 20 minutes beginning at 20:20 (8:20 p.m.) for a period of 20 days.

The stadium lightings will begin Friday, April 10, and will continue through Wednesday, April 29.

Hundreds of Minnesota schools have joined this “Be The Light” movement to share the message that students and staff are missed, and to acknowledge the difficulties community members are dealing with as a result of school closures and social distancing requirements. The lighted fields and stadiums are a way to express confidence that those venues, school hallways and school classrooms will one day be filled again.

Please note that Tiger Stadium will remain closed to the public during this time, and please continue to practice social distancing so that we can all be together again soon.

"Students need to be focused on staying healthy and continuing to learn," said U.S. Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos. "Teachers need to be able to focus on remote learning and other adaptations. Neither students nor teachers need to be focused on high-stakes tests during this difficult time. Students are simply too unlikely to be able to perform their best in this environment."

post_text:
Congratulations to senior wrestler Edward Hajas, who is one of only 28 wrestlers in the state named to the 2020 Minnesota Wrestling Coaches Association Academic All-State Team. He is also just the fifth wrestler in Delano history to be so honored.

"Edward is an outstanding leader and teammate in our program," said DHS wrestling coach Jeff Olson. "He is a near-perfect representation of what a student-athlete should be - someone who pursues and commits themselves to excellence in the academic classroom as well as their athletics and activities."

Previous Delano students to receive this honor were:
Cody Socher (2008)
Kevin Kneisl (2016)
Tucker Sjomeling (2016 and 2017)
Reier Sjomeling (2018)

post_text: A huge congratulations to three DHS athletes who signed on to play college sports this afternoon. Tate Pappas will run Division I cross country and track at the University of Illinois Chicago, Grace Glasrud will play Division I hockey for Post University in Connecticut, and Max Otto will play Division II football and baseball at Northern State University in South Dakota. It's been a joy watching you compete in Delano, and best of luck at the next level!

As someone who debuted as a children’s author and illustrator just after her retirement as a teacher, Debbie Hoven had a message for students when she visited Delano Elementary School earlier this week.

“You’re never too young, you’re never too old,” she said. “Don’t be afraid to challenge yourself and step outside your box.”

See more about Hoven's author-in-residence visit at bit.ly/AuthorDES20.

Pursing his passion for music has led Jason Koets to a career that perfectly harmonizes his interests and aptitudes.

In recognition of the Delano High School band director’s outstanding work with students, his fellow faculty members have named Koets the Delano Public Schools 2019-20 Teacher of the Year.

Read a feature on Koets at bit.ly/Koets20, and please join us in congratulating him here!

A small group of DHS actors will enter subsection competition this weekend, performing a little-known one act that carries a big message.

“I’ve never seen a high school do it,” said DHS language arts teacher and play director Joe Lawrence of Delano’s production, “I Will Go … I Will Go …” by Glen Berger.

Read about the unique challenges of portraying the first successful swim across the English Channel by an American, and the costs of that adventure, at bit.ly/DHS1Act20, and come check out tomorrow night's public performance at 6:45 p.m. in the PAC!

post_text:
Out of difficult circumstances, a multi-state movement has emerged to share comfort and hope with hospitalized children. Kimberly Rogers, a fifth-grader at Delano Intermediate School, is bringing that movement to the Delano community through a collection drive for Jessy’s Toy Box from Monday, Jan. 20, through Friday, Feb. 7. Items for children age 0-18 can be dropped off at the high school.

“When he died it was really sad because our family was really close to his,” Rogers said of Jessy, who started the program to help other children endure their hospital visits. “He was a really good kid.”

Find out more at bit.ly/JessysToyBox.
